Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: This section explains the concept of hypothesis testing for game optimization.

Hypothesis testing is a method to identify performance bottlenecks in a game. The process involves forming a hypothesis about a potential cause of slowdown, such as believing that sprites are negatively impacting performance. This hypothesis can then be tested by observing the game's performance under different conditions, like adding or removing sprites. If the initial hypothesis is confirmed, further investigation can be done. For instance, if sprites are indeed causing slowdowns, one might hypothesize that the size of the sprites is the determining factor. This secondary hypothesis can be tested by keeping all other game elements constant and varying only the sprite sizes, then measuring the performance impact. This iterative process of hypothesizing and testing helps pinpoint specific areas for optimization.
---CHUNK---
Document: General Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: This section describes a binary search method for identifying performance bottlenecks in your game.

Binary search is a technique for finding performance bottlenecks. If you suspect frames are taking too long but are unsure of the cause, you can start by commenting out roughly half of the routines that execute during a normal frame. Observe if the performance improvement is more or less than anticipated. By repeating this process on the half that still contains the bottleneck, you can progressively narrow down the problematic area until you've identified the specific cause.
---CHUNK---
