Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: This section discusses the principles of optimization, emphasizing the importance of focusing on critical parts of the code and avoiding premature optimization.

Principles
Donald Knuth said: "Programmers waste enormous amounts of time thinking about, or worrying about, the speed of noncritical parts of their programs, and these attempts at efficiency actually have a strong negative impact when debugging and maintenance are considered. We should forget about small efficiencies, say about 97% of the time: premature optimization is the root of all evil. Yet we should not pass up our opportunities in that critical 3%."

The messages are very important:
- Developer time is limited. Instead of blindly trying to speed up all aspects of a program, we should concentrate our efforts on the aspects that really matter.
- Efforts at optimization often end up with code that is harder to read and debug than non-optimized code. It is in our interests to limit this to areas that will really benefit.

Just because we can optimize a particular bit of code, it doesn't necessarily mean that we should. Knowing when and when not to optimize is a great skill to develop.

One misleading aspect of the quote is that people tend to focus on the subquote "premature optimization is the root of all evil". While premature optimization is (by definition) undesirable, performant software is the result of performant design.
---CHUNK---
Document: General Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: This section emphasizes the importance of considering performance during the initial design phase of a project, especially in game development.

Performant design
The most important time to consider performance is at the design stage, before development begins. If the design or algorithms of a program are inefficient, then no amount of later optimization will make it run as fast as a program designed for performance from the start. This principle is particularly crucial in game and graphics programming, where a performant design, even without low-level optimization, can yield significantly better results than a mediocre design with extensive low-level tuning.
---CHUNK---
Document: General Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: Discusses incremental design and the importance of avoiding premature optimization, highlighting CPU limitations due to memory bandwidth and the benefits of data-oriented design for cache locality.
Incremental design is an important part of the development process. Unless you have prior knowledge, it's unlikely you'll create the optimal design on the first attempt. Instead, you'll often create multiple versions of a code section, trying different approaches until you find a satisfactory solution. It's crucial not to get bogged down in minor details during this phase until the overall design is finalized, as much of your work might be discarded otherwise.

Providing general guidelines for performant design is challenging due to its problem-specific nature. However, one notable point regarding the CPU is that modern processors are frequently bottlenecked by memory bandwidth. This has led to a renewed interest in data-oriented design. This approach involves structuring data and algorithms to optimize for cache locality and linear memory access, rather than frequently jumping around in memory.
---CHUNK---
Document: General Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: Describes the iterative process of identifying and optimizing performance bottlenecks in a project.
The optimization process involves identifying the biggest bottlenecks, optimizing them, and then profiling again to find the next bottleneck. This iterative process ensures that optimization efforts are focused on the areas that yield the most significant performance improvements. The steps are: 1. Profile / Identify bottleneck. 2. Optimize bottleneck. 3. Return to step 1.
---CHUNK---
Document: General Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/general_optimization.rst
Summary: This section discusses strategies for optimizing performance bottlenecks in game development, focusing on algorithm and data structure improvements, pre-calculation, and code refactoring.

Optimizing bottlenecks
Some profilers will even tell you which part of a function (which data accesses, calculations) are slowing things down.

As with design, you should concentrate your efforts first on making sure the algorithms and data structures are the best they can be. Data access should be local (to make best use of CPU cache), and it can often be better to use compact storage of data (again, always profile to test results). Often, you precalculate heavy computations ahead of time. This can be done by performing the computation when loading a level, by loading a file containing precalculated data, or by storing the results of complex calculations into a script constant and reading its value.

Once algorithms and data are good, you can often make small changes in routines which improve performance. For instance, you can move some calculations outside of loops or transform nested for loops into non-nested loops. (This should be feasible if you know a 2D array's width or height in advance.)

Always retest your timing/bottlenecks after making each change. Some changes will increase speed, others may have a negative effect. Sometimes, a small positive effect will be outweighed by the negatives of more complex code, and you may choose to leave out that optimization.
---CHUNK---
